msgid "Using the Braille Cursor"
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cthe_braille_cursor.htm%2Bhtml.body.p:18-1
msgid ""
"The Braille Cursor allows you to review text in a document, separate from "
"any of the other cursors in JAWS. Unlike the other JAWS cursors, the Braille "
"Cursor is not limited to one particular character. Instead, the term Braille "
"Cursor refers to the line of text currently shown on the braille display. As "
"you use a braille display, you may notice raised or blinking dots under one "
"character. The dots represent the active cursor, which is usually the PC "
"cursor."
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cthe_braille_cursor.htm%2Bhtml.body.p:19-1
msgid ""
"Movement of the Braille Cursor is done solely through the use of the display "
"that you are using. Some displays may have commands that are not available "
"to others, and the commands to perform each action vary. Some of the "
"commands available using most or all displays include:"
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cthe_braille_cursor.htm%2Bhtml.body.ul.li:21-1
msgid "Move the Braille Cursor up or down by line"
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cthe_braille_cursor.htm%2Bhtml.body.ul.li:22-1
msgid "Move the active cursor up or down by line"
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cthe_braille_cursor.htm%2Bhtml.body.ul.li:23-1
msgid "Route the Braille Cursor to either the JAWS or PC cursor"
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cthe_braille_cursor.htm%2Bhtml.body.ul.li:24-1
msgid "Link or unlink the Braille Cursor to the active cursor"
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cthe_braille_cursor.htm%2Bhtml.body.ul.li:25-1
msgid "Pan left or right on the current line"
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cthe_braille_cursor.htm%2Bhtml.body.ul.li:26-1
msgid "Route the PC Cursor to a particular character on the braille display"
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cthe_braille_cursor.htm%2Bhtml.body.h2:28-1
msgid "Linking Cursors"
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cthe_braille_cursor.htm%2Bhtml.body.p:29-1
msgid ""
"JAWS provides three ways to link your Braille Cursor with the active cursor. "
"Each of these modes can be helpful at different times, and can be changed "
"through Settings Center."
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cthe_braille_cursor.htm%2Bhtml.body.p:30-1
msgid ""
"The Braille Cursor can be completely unlinked from the active cursor. This "
"allows you to navigate using either the Braille or the active cursor, "
"without changing the position of the other. However, if you change the "
"active cursor from JAWS to PC or vice versa, the Braille Cursor moves to the "
"location of the activated cursor."
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cthe_braille_cursor.htm%2Bhtml.body.p:31-1
msgid ""
"The Braille Cursor can be set to follow the active cursor. In this mode, "
"moving the active cursor causes the Braille Cursor to move. You can still "
"move the Braille Cursor without moving the active cursor. Most braille "
"displays have a command which can be used to toggle between this mode and "
"the previous one."
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cthe_braille_cursor.htm%2Bhtml.body.p:32-1
msgid ""
"You can choose to tether the Braille Cursor to the active cursor. In this "
"mode, moving either the Braille or the active cursor causes the other to "
"move. When moving the Braille Cursor, the active cursor follows but does not "
"cause JAWS to speak."
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cthe_braille_cursor.htm%2Bhtml.body.p:33-1
msgid ""
"<strong style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Note</strong>: The above options only "
"affect line mode. If you use <a href=\"braille.chm::/"
"Braille_Display_Modes.htm#Structured_Mode\">structured mode</a>, and are "
"viewing a structured line, movement of either the Braille or the active "
"cursor automatically moves both cursors."
msgstr ""

